                    Diana P. Rojas1, Ingrid B. Rabe1 & Maria D. Van Kerkhove1

Nature Health

(2026) Cite this article

Subjects

            Environmental healthViral infection

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

Zika virus (ZIKV) is a mosquito-borne flavivirus that was first identified in Uganda in 1947 and remained in relative obscurity for decades until an outbreak occurred on Yap Island, Micronesia, in 20071,2. The first indications of Zika posing a more serious public health threat included the detection of increased cases of Guillain–Barré syndrome and other neurological complications in adults during the outbreak in French Polynesia in 2013–2014, followed by the emergence and expansion of Zika in the Americas in 2015 and the concurrent detection of severe congenital malformations, particularly microcephaly, in infants born to women infected with ZIKV during pregnancy3,4.From detection of local ZIKV transmission in April 2015 to the end of that year, Brazil reported more than 500,000 suspected cases of Zika and growing numbers of cases of neonatal microcephaly in the Zika-affected areas5. Over the course of the evolving outbreak and spread beyond Brazil, three epidemiological alerts were issued by the World Health Organziation (WHO) and the Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) — the first regarding the Zika disease outbreak and the second and third related to congenital microcephaly and neurological disease.



